<h2 id="1"><strong>1. Reduce Cart Abandonment</strong></h2>



<p>Cart abandonment is a headache for online retailers.<br></p>



<p>According to one recent report by <a href="https://blog.salecycle.com/post/infographic-remarketing-report-q1-2017/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">SaleCycle</a>, <strong>75.6 percent of people put items in their online shopping cart only to leave it without completing their purchase.</strong><br></p>



<p>We’ve written a lot about cart abandonment on our blog, <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/abandoned-cart-emails" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">here</a> and <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/cart-abandonment-popup-examples" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">here</a>, so I won’t repeat myself. Instead, I’ll share a recent example that nailed their cart recovery email.<br></p>



<p>While writing about <a href="https://sleeknote.com/blog/beardbrand-marketing" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)">Beardbrand</a>, a men’s grooming company, I went through their checkout and abandoned my cart.<br></p>



<p>After doing so, they sent me the following email:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="595" height="495" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email.png" alt="Beardbrand Cart Recovery Email" class="wp-image-82742" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email.png 595w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-300x250.png 300w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-380x316.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-42x35.png 42w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-60x50.png 60w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-589x490.png 589w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-220x183.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-385x320.png 385w" sizes="(max-width: 595px) 100vw, 595px" /></figure></div>



<p>Nothing new there. We’re all familiar with cart recovery emails that focus on offering an incentive. You might even be using them yourself. And if you are, you’re following good practice.<br></p>



<p>But what I wasn’t prepared for, and what I want to draw attention to, is the second email I got a few days later, from the founder himself, Eric Bandholtz:<br></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img width="1024" height="522" src="https://sleeknote.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-1024x522.png" alt="Beardbrand Cart Recovery Email 2" class="wp-image-82738" srcset="https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-1024x522.png 1024w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-300x153.png 300w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-768x391.png 768w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-1536x782.png 1536w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-380x194.png 380w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-600x306.png 600w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-760x387.png 760w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-1440x734.png 1440w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-69x35.png 69w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-98x50.png 98w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-740x377.png 740w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-220x112.png 220w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2-385x196.png 385w, https://n7nqziuw1z4b1r6k2adhav10-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Beardbrand-Cart-Recovery-Email-2.png 1590w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure></div>



<p>With its conversational nature and plain format, it’s hard to argue it’s overly-salesy or aggressive. And given they’re still sending months after I wrote my post, one can only assume it’s working like gangbusters.</p>


<div id="editors-note-block_5f71981104d02" class="block-editors-note">
